<subSubSection id="AAB96554A661FF8E4889BF5FBA5CFCE8" pageId="1" pageNumber="140" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="E21C36DFA661FF8E4889BF5FBA5CFCE8" blockId="1.[113,738,631,1786]" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">
Diagnosis. The neotropical genus 
<taxonomicName id="25A34D5CA661FF8E4A23BF50B967FD60" authorityName="Peckham &amp; Peckham" authorityYear="1894" box="[516,593,632,651]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Helvetia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D0D7EACDA661FF8E4A23BF50B967FD60" box="[516,593,632,651]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Helvetia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from all the remaining genera of the subfamily 
<taxonomicName id="25A34D5CA661FF8E4856BF9BBA33FD2C" authorityName="Petrunkevitch" authorityYear="1928" box="[113,261,691,711]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="1" pageNumber="140" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Heliophaninae">Heliophaninae</taxonomicName>
by having a trapezoid carapace, which is much wider at the posterior region than it is at the region of the anterior eye row (
<figureCitation id="7A982A5AA661FF8E4903BFC7BA6AFCE8" box="[292,348,751,771]" captionStart="Figures 4-10" captionStartId="4.[189,256,1381,1401]" captionTargetBox="[201,1451,197,1372]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[197,1446,189,1376]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figures 4-10. Epigynum of (4-5) Helvetia cancrimana: (4) ventral view̡ (5) dorsal view; (6-7) Helvetia labiata: (6) ventral view̡ (7) dorsal view; (8-10) Helvetia semialba: (8) female holotype̡ dorsal view̡ (9) epigynum̡ vental view̡ (10) dorsal view. Bars = 0.25 mm̡ except for fig. 8 = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678506" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3678506/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="AAB96554A661FF8E4889BE25BBF8F937" pageId="1" pageNumber="140" type="description">
<paragraph id="E21C36DFA661FF8E4889BE25BBF8F937" blockId="1.[113,738,631,1786]" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">
Description. Small spiders (about 
<quantity id="255B9B3AA661FF8E49D1BE25B975FCCA" box="[502,579,781,801]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="140" unit="mm" value="4.5" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="3.0">3-6 mm</quantity>
) with low, elongated carapace and long abdomen (
<figureCitation id="7A982A5AA661FF8E49C3BE02B92BFCD5" box="[484,541,810,830]" captionStart="Figures 1-3" captionStartId="2.[189,256,1210,1230]" captionTargetBox="[189,1474,195,1202]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[265,1399,186,715]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figures 1-3. Helvetia cancrimana: (1) male̡ laterodorsal view̡ arrows show the stridulatory apparatus on femur I and carapace; (2) stridulatory apparatus̡ rugose portion of lateral carapace; (3) modified femoral setae of the stridulatory apparatus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678504" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3678504/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Abdominal color patterns include pairs of light patches on a dark background, which can be fused forming transverse stripes (
<figureCitation id="7A982A5AA661FF8E4A45BE4EB9AAFC91" box="[610,668,870,890]" captionStart="Figures 1-3" captionStartId="2.[189,256,1210,1230]" captionTargetBox="[189,1474,195,1202]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[265,1399,186,715]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figures 1-3. Helvetia cancrimana: (1) male̡ laterodorsal view̡ arrows show the stridulatory apparatus on femur I and carapace; (2) stridulatory apparatus̡ rugose portion of lateral carapace; (3) modified femoral setae of the stridulatory apparatus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678504" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3678504/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), dark abdomen with a large patch of light scales covering the entire abdomen and longitudinal stripes of dark scales on a light background (
<figureCitation id="7A982A5AA661FF8E48E0BEE8BBC8FC3F" box="[199,254,960,980]" captionStart="Figures 4-10" captionStartId="4.[189,256,1381,1401]" captionTargetBox="[201,1451,197,1372]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[197,1446,189,1376]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figures 4-10. Epigynum of (4-5) Helvetia cancrimana: (4) ventral view̡ (5) dorsal view; (6-7) Helvetia labiata: (6) ventral view̡ (7) dorsal view; (8-10) Helvetia semialba: (8) female holotype̡ dorsal view̡ (9) epigynum̡ vental view̡ (10) dorsal view. Bars = 0.25 mm̡ except for fig. 8 = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678506" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3678506/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
). Chelicerae about one third of carapace length, almost vertical (
<figureCitation id="7A982A5AA661FF8E4934BEF5BA7FFC1A" box="[275,329,989,1009]" captionStart="Figures 1-3" captionStartId="2.[189,256,1210,1230]" captionTargetBox="[189,1474,195,1202]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[265,1399,186,715]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figures 1-3. Helvetia cancrimana: (1) male̡ laterodorsal view̡ arrows show the stridulatory apparatus on femur I and carapace; (2) stridulatory apparatus̡ rugose portion of lateral carapace; (3) modified femoral setae of the stridulatory apparatus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678504" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3678504/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
), with two teeth on promargin and one on retromargin. Legs Iusually strongest and darkest, strongly developed in some species (
<figureCitation id="7A982A5AA661FF8E49A7B931BA82FBC6" box="[384,436,1049,1069]" captionStart="Figures 1-3" captionStartId="2.[189,256,1210,1230]" captionTargetBox="[189,1474,195,1202]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[265,1399,186,715]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figures 1-3. Helvetia cancrimana: (1) male̡ laterodorsal view̡ arrows show the stridulatory apparatus on femur I and carapace; (2) stridulatory apparatus̡ rugose portion of lateral carapace; (3) modified femoral setae of the stridulatory apparatus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678504" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3678504/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Palps have the heliophanine bump and can have a short embolus, originating distally on the prolateral side of the tegulum and a short RTA (
<figureCitation id="7A982A5AA661FF8E4A48B97DBBBDFB6C" captionStart="Figures 15-20" captionStartId="6.[189,256,1173,1193]" captionTargetBox="[352,1306,201,1167]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[344,1309,189,1172]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figures 15-20. Left palp of (15-16) Helvetia galianoae: (15) ventral view̡ (16) retrolateral view; (17-18) Helvetia humillima: (17) ventral view̡ (18) retrolateral view; (19-20) Helvetia stridulans: (19) vental view̡ (20) retrolareal view. Bars = 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678513" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3678513/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Figs 15 and 16</figureCitation>
), or can exhibit extensive modifications, such as a very long embolus associated with a counterclockwise rotation of the tegulum in the left palp (
<figureCitation id="7A982A5AA661FF8E4957B987BA80FB28" box="[368,438,1199,1219]" captionStart="Figures 15-20" captionStartId="6.[189,256,1173,1193]" captionTargetBox="[352,1306,201,1167]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[344,1309,189,1172]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figures 15-20. Left palp of (15-16) Helvetia galianoae: (15) ventral view̡ (16) retrolateral view; (17-18) Helvetia humillima: (17) ventral view̡ (18) retrolateral view; (19-20) Helvetia stridulans: (19) vental view̡ (20) retrolareal view. Bars = 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678513" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3678513/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
), grooves on the cymbium to hold the tip of the curling embolus (
<figureCitation id="7A982A5AA661FF8E49C7B9E5B913FB0A" box="[480,549,1229,1249]" captionStart="Figures 15-20" captionStartId="6.[189,256,1173,1193]" captionTargetBox="[352,1306,201,1167]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[344,1309,189,1172]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figures 15-20. Left palp of (15-16) Helvetia galianoae: (15) ventral view̡ (16) retrolateral view; (17-18) Helvetia humillima: (17) ventral view̡ (18) retrolateral view; (19-20) Helvetia stridulans: (19) vental view̡ (20) retrolareal view. Bars = 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678513" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3678513/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
), bifid RTA, with a developed ventral branch (
<figureCitation id="7A982A5AA661FF8E49A0B9C2BAFBFB15" box="[391,461,1258,1278]" captionStart="Figures 15-20" captionStartId="6.[189,256,1173,1193]" captionTargetBox="[352,1306,201,1167]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[344,1309,189,1172]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figures 15-20. Left palp of (15-16) Helvetia galianoae: (15) ventral view̡ (16) retrolateral view; (17-18) Helvetia humillima: (17) ventral view̡ (18) retrolateral view; (19-20) Helvetia stridulans: (19) vental view̡ (20) retrolareal view. Bars = 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678513" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3678513/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
) or with a very developed dorsal branch (see 
<bibRefCitation id="86324B2EA661FF8E4912B821BA88FAF7" author="GALIANO" box="[309,446,1288,1308]" firstAuthor="GALIANO" journalOrPublisher="Revista de la Sociedad Entomologica Argentina" pageId="1" pageNumber="140" pagination="51 - 56" part="35" refId="ref6535" refString="GALIANO, M. E. 1976. Dos nuevas especies del genero Helvetia Peckham, 1894 (Araneae, Salticidae). Revista de la Sociedad Entomologica Argentina 35: 51 - 56." title="Dos nuevas especies del genero Helvetia Peckham, 1894 (Araneae, Salticidae)" type="journal article" year="1976">GALIANO 1976</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 10). Epigyna vary from very short copulatory ducts (
<figureCitation id="7A982A5AA661FF8E49B3B80EB938FAD1" box="[404,526,1318,1338]" captionStart="Figures 4-10" captionStartId="4.[189,256,1381,1401]" captionTargetBox="[201,1451,197,1372]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[197,1446,189,1376]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figures 4-10. Epigynum of (4-5) Helvetia cancrimana: (4) ventral view̡ (5) dorsal view; (6-7) Helvetia labiata: (6) ventral view̡ (7) dorsal view; (8-10) Helvetia semialba: (8) female holotype̡ dorsal view̡ (9) epigynum̡ vental view̡ (10) dorsal view. Bars = 0.25 mm̡ except for fig. 8 = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678506" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3678506/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Figs 4 and 5</figureCitation>
) to coiled, very long copulatory ducts (
<figureCitation id="7A982A5AA661FF8E4900B86CBAB9FAB3" box="[295,399,1348,1368]" captionStart="Figures 11-14" captionStartId="5.[113,180,1154,1174]" captionTargetBox="[248,1259,194,1141]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[242,1263,181,1150]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figures 11-14. Epigynum of (11-12) Helvetia santarema: (11) ventral view̡ (12) dorsal view; (13-14) Helvetia albovittata: (13) ventral view̡ (14) dorsal view. Bars = 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678508" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3678508/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Figs 11-14</figureCitation>
), on whose medial part there is a pair of glandular swollen areas; copulatory openings are usually well separated from each other (
<figureCitation id="7A982A5AA661FF8E49C1B8A8B961FA78" box="[486,599,1408,1428]" captionStart="Figures 4-10" captionStartId="4.[189,256,1381,1401]" captionTargetBox="[201,1451,197,1372]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[197,1446,189,1376]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figures 4-10. Epigynum of (4-5) Helvetia cancrimana: (4) ventral view̡ (5) dorsal view; (6-7) Helvetia labiata: (6) ventral view̡ (7) dorsal view; (8-10) Helvetia semialba: (8) female holotype̡ dorsal view̡ (9) epigynum̡ vental view̡ (10) dorsal view. Bars = 0.25 mm̡ except for fig. 8 = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678506" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3678506/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Figs 4, 6, 9</figureCitation>
, and 13), but can be found close together, forming a median small atrium (
<figureCitation id="7A982A5AA661FF8E485FB894BB8BFA3B" box="[120,189,1468,1488]" captionStart="Figures 11-14" captionStartId="5.[113,180,1154,1174]" captionTargetBox="[248,1259,194,1141]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[242,1263,181,1150]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figures 11-14. Epigynum of (11-12) Helvetia santarema: (11) ventral view̡ (12) dorsal view; (13-14) Helvetia albovittata: (13) ventral view̡ (14) dorsal view. Bars = 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678508" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3678508/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
) or on the internal wall of a very large, deep atrium (
<figureCitation id="7A982A5AA661FF8E4850B8F1BA22FA06" box="[119,276,1497,1517]" captionStart="Figures 21-24" captionStartId="7.[114,181,1116,1136]" captionTargetBox="[254,1255,198,1101]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[249,1256,189,1104]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figures 21-24. Epigynum of (21-22) Helvetia rinaldiae: (21) ventral view̡ (22) dorsal view; (23-24) Helvetia roeweri: (23) ventral view̡ (24) dorsal view. Bars = 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678517" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3678517/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Figs 21 and 22</figureCitation>
); the epigynal pockets can be fused (
<figureCitation id="7A982A5AA661FF8E4ABEB8F1B9E3FA06" box="[665,725,1497,1517]" captionStart="Figures 4-10" captionStartId="4.[189,256,1381,1401]" captionTargetBox="[201,1451,197,1372]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[197,1446,189,1376]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figures 4-10. Epigynum of (4-5) Helvetia cancrimana: (4) ventral view̡ (5) dorsal view; (6-7) Helvetia labiata: (6) ventral view̡ (7) dorsal view; (8-10) Helvetia semialba: (8) female holotype̡ dorsal view̡ (9) epigynum̡ vental view̡ (10) dorsal view. Bars = 0.25 mm̡ except for fig. 8 = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678506" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3678506/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
), medially placed (
<figureCitation id="7A982A5AA661FF8E493AB8DFBA93F9E0" box="[285,421,1527,1547]" captionStart="Figures 4-10" captionStartId="4.[189,256,1381,1401]" captionTargetBox="[201,1451,197,1372]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[197,1446,189,1376]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figures 4-10. Epigynum of (4-5) Helvetia cancrimana: (4) ventral view̡ (5) dorsal view; (6-7) Helvetia labiata: (6) ventral view̡ (7) dorsal view; (8-10) Helvetia semialba: (8) female holotype̡ dorsal view̡ (9) epigynum̡ vental view̡ (10) dorsal view. Bars = 0.25 mm̡ except for fig. 8 = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678506" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3678506/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Figs 7 and 10</figureCitation>
) or separated into a pair of lateral pockets (
<figureCitation id="7A982A5AA661FF8E48D4BB3DBAB0F9C2" box="[243,390,1557,1577]" captionStart="Figures 11-14" captionStartId="5.[113,180,1154,1174]" captionTargetBox="[248,1259,194,1141]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[242,1263,181,1150]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figures 11-14. Epigynum of (11-12) Helvetia santarema: (11) ventral view̡ (12) dorsal view; (13-14) Helvetia albovittata: (13) ventral view̡ (14) dorsal view. Bars = 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678508" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3678508/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Figs 12 and 14</figureCitation>
), which can be connected in some species. The stridulatory apparatus consists in this group of a series of three modified setae dorsally on the distal portion of the femur I (
<figureCitation id="7A982A5AA661FF8E48C9BB47BA51F968" box="[238,359,1647,1667]" captionStart="Figures 1-3" captionStartId="2.[189,256,1210,1230]" captionTargetBox="[189,1474,195,1202]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[265,1399,186,715]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figures 1-3. Helvetia cancrimana: (1) male̡ laterodorsal view̡ arrows show the stridulatory apparatus on femur I and carapace; (2) stridulatory apparatus̡ rugose portion of lateral carapace; (3) modified femoral setae of the stridulatory apparatus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678504" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3678504/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Figs 1 and 3</figureCitation>
) and a granulose area laterally on the anterior portion of the carapace (
<figureCitation id="7A982A5AA661FF8E499DBBA5B902F94A" box="[442,564,1677,1697]" captionStart="Figures 1-3" captionStartId="2.[189,256,1210,1230]" captionTargetBox="[189,1474,195,1202]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[265,1399,186,715]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figures 1-3. Helvetia cancrimana: (1) male̡ laterodorsal view̡ arrows show the stridulatory apparatus on femur I and carapace; (2) stridulatory apparatus̡ rugose portion of lateral carapace; (3) modified femoral setae of the stridulatory apparatus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3678504" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3678504/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Figs 1 and 2</figureCitation>
), extending from the anterior lateral eyes to the region behind the posterior lateral eyes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="AAB96554A661FF8E4889BBCEB9B8F911" box="[174,654,1766,1786]" pageId="1" pageNumber="140" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="E21C36DFA661FF8E4889BBCEB9B8F911" blockId="1.[113,738,631,1786]" box="[174,654,1766,1786]" pageId="1" pageNumber="140">Distribution. Known only from South America.</paragraph>
